Explains how to translate application on web and mobile.

# On web application

The core functionnality per apps are located in ~/lib/i18n

But the Trans component returns a React.ReactElement type, sometimes you may need string type.

### 1.1 Using string translations in client side

Use the `useTranslation` hook from react-i18next when I you have to translate a string client side.
Avoid using as jsx, use `<Trans />` instead.

```tsx
'use client';

import { useTranslation } from 'react-i18next';

export function MyComponent() {
  const { t, i18n: {language: locale} } = useTranslation('common');
  // the locale var contains the active language code   
  
  return <Button aria-label={{t('homeTabLabel')}}>
    <Trans i18nKey="auth.signUpTitle" ns="dashboard" >
  </Button>;
}
```

### 1.2 Using string translations in server side

Use the `useTranslation` hook from react-i18next:

```tsx
'use client';

import { getServerI18n } from '~/lib/i18n.server';

export async function generateMetadata() {
  const { t, language } = await getServerI18n();
  // the language var contains the active language code   

  return {
    title: t('marketing:contact'),
  };
}

export function ContactPage() {
  const { t } = await getServerI18n();
  
  return <h1>{t('marketing:homeTabLabel')}</h1>;
}

export default ContactPage;
```

### 2 How use dynamic data in string

```json
{
  "key": "{{what}} is {{how}}",
  "keyWithDataModel": "I am {{author.name}}"
}
```

````ts
// ...
t('key', { what: 'i18next', how: 'great' });

const author = { 
    name: 'Jan',
    github: 'jamuhl'
};
t('keyWithDataModel', { author });
// ...
````

### 2.1 How use custom tags

```json
{
  "myKey": "This is a <CustomLink href=\"https://example.com/\">link to example.com</CustomLink>."
}
```

````tsx
// ...
<Trans
  i18nKey="myKey"
  components={{ 
    CustomLink: <MyCustomLinkComponent href="value-to-be-overridden"/> 
  }}
/>
// ...
````

## 3 Call `await getServerI18n();` at the top of your app

Calling `getServerI18n` will initialize the i18n instance, and allow you to pass the language to your html tree.

```typescript
import React from 'react';
import { getServerI18n } from '~/lib/i18n.server';

export default async function RootLayout({ children }: React.PropsWithChildren): Promise<React.JSX.Element> {
    const { language } = await getServerI18n();
    // ...

    return (
        <html lang={language} className={className} suppressHydrationWarning>
        // ...
        </html>
    );
}

```

